{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17601997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17601997"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:20:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:20:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15675"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15675"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.98,0,0.02,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8366"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62210"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8366"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15675"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47656"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7072"},{"type":"tags","id":"7098"},{"type":"tags","id":"7099"},{"type":"tags","id":"10521"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20167"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20170"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62210"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most significant anatomical difference between the male and female urethra?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The female urethra contains more elastic fibres","The female urethra is shorter and straighter","The male urethra has fewer mucous glands","The female urethra has more striated muscle","The male urethra has fewer transitional epithelial cells"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe key anatomical differences between male and female urethras are significant for both clinical practice and understanding disease patterns. \u003Cstrong\u003EThe female urethra is shorter and straighter\u003C/strong\u003E, measuring 3-4 cm in length with a relatively straight course from the bladder to the external meatus. This is in contrast to the male urethra which is approximately 20 cm long and follows an S-shaped course.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe statement that \u003Cstrong\u003Ethe female urethra contains more elastic fibres\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Both male and female urethras contain similar proportions of elastic fibres, which help maintain urethral tone and facilitate micturition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe male urethra has fewer mucous glands\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The male urethra actually contains more glands, including the prostatic glands and bulbourethral glands, which are not present in females.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe male urethra has fewer transitional epithelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Both male and female urethras have similar epithelial composition, with transitional epithelium proximally changing to stratified squamous epithelium distally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe female urethra has more striated muscle\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Both male and female urethras have similar muscular components, with the external urethral sphincter composed of striated muscle in both sexes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe shorter length and straighter course of the female urethra has important clinical implications. It explains why women are more susceptible to urinary tract infections, as bacteria have a shorter distance to travel to reach the bladder. It also explains why female catheterisation is generally easier to perform than male catheterisation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The female urethra is shorter (3-4 cm) compared to the male urethra (20 cm) and has a straight course.","The male urethra has distinct anatomical regions (prostatic, membranous, and penile/spongy) and follows an S-shaped course.","Understanding urethral anatomy is crucial for catheterisation and explains different susceptibilities to urinary tract infections."],"references":["Jung J, Ahn HK, Huh Y. Clinical and functional anatomy of the urethral sphincter. Int Neurourol J. 2012 Sep;16(3):102-6. doi: 10.5213/inj.2012.16.3.102. Epub 2012 Sep 30. PMID: 23094214; PMCID: PMC3469827.","Abelson B, Sun D, Que L, Nebel RA, Baker D, Popiel P, Amundsen CL, Chai T, Close C, DiSanto M, Fraser MO, Kielb SJ, Kuchel G, Mueller ER, Palmer MH, Parker-Autry C, Wolfe AJ, Damaser MS. Sex differences in lower urinary tract biology and physiology. Biol Sex Differ. 2018 Oct 22;9(1):45. doi: 10.1186/s13293-018-0204-8. PMID: 30343668; PMCID: PMC6196569.","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press.","Kovacs, W. J., \u0026 Ojeda, S. R. (Eds.). (2012). Textbook of endocrine physiology. OUP USA."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47656"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15675"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47656"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T12:56:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T12:57:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8366"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62210"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"a